GSE120221 - Human marrow single cell RNA seq: Cell annotation and batch correction integration

In this note, we are going to do two tasks. The first task is we will identify cell types (cell annotation) in human marrow scRNAseq from GSE120221. We will use a reference dataset where cells were annotated to identify cell types of a new dataset. There are many tools to do that, we only apply SingleR method in this note. A little more details about SingleR, it finds the correlations between cells and differential express from cell’s features.

We are loading data that we need to annotate. Our dataset is human marrow dataset GSM3396161. You can download it by using google.

To use SingleR, we have to make sure both datasets have the same features. One way to do it is we take the common features from both datasets, and it is what we are doing next.

Before we do cell annotation, I would like to take a look at our dataset, do some cluster analysis, then we compare the results how our cell identifying works. We are using Seurat for those tasks

Now, we load out reference dataset (download from this link https://ndownloader.figshare.com/files/27686835). You may need to convert to suerat object by using SeuratDisk first and load to seurat object later

Since SingleR works with SingleCellExperiment object only, we need to covert to singlecellexperiment objects

sce_human_marrow <- as.SingleCellExperiment(human_cd34_bone_marrow)
sceGSM3396161 <- as.SingleCellExperiment(seuratGSM3396161)

Extract count matrices

df_GSM <- as.data.frame(sceGSM3396161@assays@data$counts)
df_cd4 <- as.data.frame(sce_human_marrow@assays@data$counts)

Change rownames to column if you have not

df_GSM <- rownames_to_column(df_GSM,"genes")
df_cd4 <- rownames_to_column(df_cd4,"genes")

Find the common features of both datasets

common_gene <- base::intersect(df_GSM$genes, df_cd4$genes)

Filter the count matrices to get only common features

not_in_GSM <- base::setdiff(df_GSM$genes, common_gene)
com_genes_df_GSM <- df_GSM %>% arrange(genes) %>% filter(!is.element(genes, not_in_GSM ))
not_in_cd4 <- setdiff(df_cd4$genes, common_gene)
com_genes_df_cd4 <- df_cd4 %>% arrange(genes) %>% filter(!is.element(genes, not_in_cd4 ))

Check if we did it right

nrow(com_genes_df_cd4) == nrow(com_genes_df_GSM)
[1] TRUE
setequal(com_genes_df_cd4$genes, com_genes_df_GSM$genes)
[1] TRUE

Switch back gene column to rowname so we get the count matrix

colnames(com_genes_df_cd4) <- c("genes", as.character(sce_human_marrow$clusters))
com_genes_df_cd4 <- column_to_rownames(com_genes_df_cd4, "genes")

Create singlecellexperiment object

sce_cd4 <- SingleCellExperiment(assays = list(counts = as.matrix(com_genes_df_cd4)))
com_genes_df_GSM <- column_to_rownames(com_genes_df_GSM, "genes")
sce_GSM <- SingleCellExperiment(assays = list(counts = as.matrix(com_genes_df_GSM)))

Compute the lognormal counts by scuttle library

sce_GSM <- scuttle::logNormCounts(sce_GSM)
sce_cd4 <- scuttle::logNormCounts(sce_cd4)

Run SingleR to annotate cells

We first make a training for our reference dataset so we can use later for our needed dataset

trained <- trainSingleR(sce_cd4, label=colnames(sce_cd4))

Run the prediction for cells (it takes a while to run the program)

pred <- classifySingleR(sce_GSM, trained)

Assign the predicted cell name to each cell

colnames(sce_GSM) <- pred$labels

Create a copy of seurat object and assign the cluster name by cell types and plot UMAP

seurat_sce_GSM <- seuratGSM3396161
seurat_sce_GSM$orig.ident <- colnames(sce_GSM)
DimPlot(object = seurat_sce_GSM, reduction = "umap", group.by = "orig.ident", sizes.highlight = TRUE)

Next, we work on a different task. If you have 2 different datasets from 2 difference experience or different batches. We may want to combine 2 dataset as one and we want to minimize the batch effects (batch correction). Here is a way to do it.

Merge 2 datasets from 2 experiments (You may not need this step but I prefer to merge dataset to get the same features for all datasets first).

Let us start from creating seurat objects

bone_count <- human_cd34_bone_marrow@assays$RNA@counts

seurat_marrow_cd4 <- CreateSeuratObject(counts = bone_count, project = "bone_cd4")

rownames(count_GSM3396161)<- genes_GSM3396161$symbol
colnames(count_GSM3396161) <- colnames(sce_GSM) # Using the cell names we identify
seuratGSM3396161 <- CreateSeuratObject(counts = count_GSM3396161, project = "GSM3396161")
Warning: Non-unique features (rownames) present in the input matrix, making unique
Warning: Non-unique cell names (colnames) present in the input matrix, making unique
Warning: Feature names cannot have underscores ('_'), replacing with dashes ('-')
seuratGSM3396161$orig.ident <- colnames(sce_GSM)
seurat_marrow_cd4$orig.ident <- as.character(human_cd34_bone_marrow$clusters)

Merge objects

merge_studies <- merge(seurat_marrow_cd4, seuratGSM3396161, add.cell.ids = c("cd4", "GSM"))

Then we split the merge into different batches

study.list <- SplitObject(merge_studies, split.by = "ident")

Normalize and identify variable features for each dataset independently


study.list <- lapply(X = study.list, FUN = function(x) {
    x <- NormalizeData(x)
    x <- FindVariableFeatures(x, selection.method = "vst", nfeatures = 2000)
})

Select features that are repeatedly variable across datasets for integration


features <- SelectIntegrationFeatures(object.list = study.list)

We then identify anchors using the FindIntegrationAnchors() function, which takes a list of Seurat objects as input, and use these anchors to integrate the two datasets together with IntegrateData()

marrow.anchors <- FindIntegrationAnchors(object.list = study.list, anchor.features = features)

Make sure we want to work with the “integrated” assay


DefaultAssay(marrow.combined) <- "integrated"

Run the standard workflow for visualization and clustering


marrow.combined <- ScaleData(marrow.combined, verbose = FALSE)

marrow.combined <- RunPCA(marrow.combined, npcs = 30, verbose = FALSE, assay = "integrated")
marrow.combined <- RunUMAP(marrow.combined, reduction = "pca", dims = 1:30)
marrow.combined <- FindNeighbors(marrow.combined, reduction = "pca", dims = 1:30)
marrow.combined <- FindClusters(marrow.combined, resolution = 0.5)
